{
  "doc_id": "27877",
  "text": "Several members of the transient receptor potential (TRP) family of cation channels have been implicated in the regulation of vascular function in health and disease. [CITATION_1] TRPM7 is a ubiquitously distributed member of the melastatin-related TRP subfamily (TRPM) of these channels. 14 It is highly permeable to Mg 2ϩ and until now, in vascular smooth muscle, it has mainly been implicated in Mg 2ϩ homeostasis. [CITATION_2] The novel discovery that its activity is enhanced by flow-induced shear stress gives it particular relevance to vascular disease. Altered Mg 2ϩ homeostasis appears to be a risk factor in The opinions expressed in this editorial are not necessarily those of the editors or of the American Heart Association. atherosclerosis. [CITATION_3] Perhaps the aberrant insertion of TRPM7 channels into the smooth muscle cell membrane contributes to this. It is possible that the flow-induced flux of Mg 2ϩ through TRPM7 channels is as important as the flux of Ca 2ϩ in the smooth muscle response to increased blood flow.",
